 ); the 2,334 myeloid transcriptomes represented 7.48% of all cell types. This cluster was defined as myeloid lineage cells based on the pan-expression of  Figure 4D 
 SIRPA ,  CSF1R , and  FCGR3A  ( 
 ).  Figure 5C 
 SIRPA  and  CSF1R  were recently confirmed to be pan-myeloid lineage markers in the characterization of the porcine immune system ( 43 ). However, we observed that markers for more precise subtypes of myeloid cells were not uniform in expression, suggesting that more specific myeloid subtypes could be elucidated. To identify these specific cell types within the myeloid cluster, we subsetted this population from the full dataset and performed principal component analysis (PCA) to generate a new UMAP, identifying eight unique clusters ( 
 ). We then generated lists of the top significant DEGs for manual identification and GSEA. Based on the overall higher expression of several MHC Class II molecules, such as  Figures 5A, B 
 SLA-DRA , and the lower relative expression of  CD163 , we identified Clusters 6, 7, and 8, as dendritic cells (Dendritic Cells A, Dendritic Cells B, and Dendritic Cells C, respectively) ( 
 ). The remaining clusters had higher relative expression of  Figure 5D 
 CD14  and  CD163  and were identified broadly as macrophages. However, we found that three out of the five macrophage clusters (Clusters 2, 3, and 4) were best classified as M2 macrophages (M2 Macrophage A, M2 Macrophage B, and M2 Macrophage C, respectively), characterized by a higher ratio of  CD206  (M2) to  CD86  (M1) and in some cases, higher expression of macrophage scavenger receptors such as  MSR1  ( 
 ). Cluster 1 was the only macrophage cluster with higher levels of  Figure 5E 
 CD86  and  SLA-DRA  and thus was classified as M1 macrophages ( 
 ). Furthermore, M1 macrophages were enriched for GO terms “Response to Cytokine” and “Immune Response,” primarily through the higher expression of  Figures 5D, E 
 CXCL8, IL1B, CCL5 , and  CXCL16  ( 
 ). Surprisingly, Cluster 5 was defined by high expression of  Supplementary Table 4 
 COL1A1, COL1A2 , and  DCN  while still expressing pan-myeloid markers ( 
 ). While this cluster was the smallest within the myeloid cell population, it was nearly exclusively represented by tumor-derived macrophages (91.53%). Fibrotic macrophages have been characterized in patients with pulmonary fibrosis and correlated with increased mortality and fibrosis ( Figure 5F 
 44 ). Additionally, a recent study using a mouse model of fibrotic scar formation in the heart has shown that monocyte-derived macrophages directly contributed to COL1A1 deposition ( 45 ). This cluster might represent a rare population of macrophages with a profound impact on a tumor microenvironment centered around extracellular matrix (ECM) reconstruction. Figure 5 Analysis of Myeloid Cell Populations:  (A)  Cluster 7 was subsetted from the full dataset for subsequent analysis.  (B)  UMAP analysis on myeloid cell subset produced 7 unique clusters.  (C–G)  Density plots highlighting gene expression intensity scaled from high (“hi”) to low (“lo”) of selected subtype markers. Subscripts adjacent to markers reflect the expected phenotype for the above cell type.  (C)  Pan-myeloid markers  SIRPA  and  + 
